{"type":"message","id":"9fb5b777","parentId":"3cdedcab","timestamp":"2026-06-03T22:55:12.240Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-befdf688d6d7ddcf","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/node/workspace/ground_truth/Agentic_Sandbox_Ground_Truth.md"},"partialArgs":"{\"path\": \"/home/node/workspace/ground_truth/Agentic_Sandbox_Ground_Truth.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"vllm","model":"RedHatAI/Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct-FP8-dynamic","usage":{"input":14613,"output":31,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":14644,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1780527304938,"responseId":"chatcmpl-a7dec6d48f6d56fe"}}
{"type":"message","id":"50a32601","parentId":"9fb5b777","timestamp":"2026-06-03T22:55:12.246Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-befdf688d6d7ddcf","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Agentic Sandbox Project (AIOS) - Ground Truth Reference Document\n\n## 1. Project Vision and Motivation\n* **Core Concept**: Design and build an industry-informed agentic innovation infrastructure, referred to as an Agentic Operating System (AIOS) or \"Sandbox\".\n* **Vision**: Create a controlled, isolated environment where deployed AI agents can execute tasks (perceive, reason, act) and collaborate with other agents without producing unintended consequences or affecting real-world enterprise systems.\n* **Motivation**: As organizations shift towards enterprise systems composed of multiple autonomous agents, the Sandbox answers a critical architectural question: *How do we architect these systems well?* It allows organizations to safely address \"what-if\" scenarios. Furthermore, it facilitates the translation of university-based AI inventions into practical industry solutions.\n* **Target Partners**: University researchers, industry organizations, non-profit organizations, and government entities.\n\n## 2. Core Features and Capabilities\nThe AIOS Sandbox will be designed to offer the following high-level capabilities:\n* **Multi-Agent Simulation**: Simulate complex AI solutions composed of a network of collaborating AI agents.\n* **Workflow Orchestration**: Orchestrate complex, multistep workflows with intricate dependencies, all driven by a defined goal or outcome.\n* **Architecture Optimization**: Provide system-level goal-seeking capabilities to optimize agentic architectures and address architectural design flaws.\n* **Continuous Improvement**: Enable self-improving mechanisms via reinforcement learning (RL) and human observation.\n* **Risk Evaluation**: Simulate and evaluate cyber risk metrics specific to multi-agent environments.\n* **Explainability & Agency**: Implement built-in capabilities to address and ensure AI explainability and maintain proper agent agency.\n* **Human Team Mirroring**: Foster widespread adoption of sophisticated multi-agent systems equipped with specialized skills that mirror human team dynamics.\n\n## 3. System Architecture & Context\nThe infrastructure of the Agentic Sandbox is conceptualized through the following layers:\n* **Computing Infrastructure**: Built upon an advanced or enhanced selection of open-source frameworks.\n* **Agentic OS / Infrastructure**: The core engine managing the deployment, integration, and execution of autonomous agents.\n* **Input Streams**:\n    * *Business/Societal Challenges*: Use cases driven by industry, non-profits, and government entities.\n    * *Agentic Innovations*: Single or multi-agent research models generated by RIT AI Research and university partners.\n* **Industry Verticals**: Integration of specialized industry capabilities and skills.\n\n**RIT Strategic Pipeline (Translation)**\nA major theme of the project is bridging the gap between theoretical academia and industry. The project supports RIT's strategic direction of driving practice-inspired AI research. It aims to translate new algorithms and faculty-led research (inventions) into tangible commercial and societal artifacts through the university's entrepreneurial ecosystem and technology transfer offices.\n\n## 4. Research Directions, Milestones, & State of the Art\n### Immediate Summer Goals\n* **Vision Paper**: The primary end-of-summer objective is to author a vision paper describing the Agentic Sandbox. This will define the agent OS, detail key functions/requirements, map out the technical systems architecture, highlight 2-3 representative use cases, and outline next steps.\n* **Prototyping & Infrastructure Evaluation**: \n    * Survey and evaluate leading infrastructure and tools for agent building and deployment (e.g., OpenClaw, Manus, OpenAI Operator). Compare and contrast these tools.\n    * Build a prototype agent to demonstrate infrastructure capabilities (led by a summer student).\n* **Use Case Identification**: Establish 2-3 specific scenarios to test the infrastructure. Current targeted domains include:\n    * Healthcare\n    * Cyber risks in multi-agentic systems\n\n### Fall Goals\n* Deepen engagement with partner universities and industry stakeholders.\n* Develop a formal funding proposal for agencies such as NIST and/or NSF.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Evaluation Criteria for Research Papers (Agent Ground Truth)\n*When using an LLM agent to review and compare research literature against this project, papers should be evaluated on their relevance to the following core investigation areas:*\n\n1. **Agent-to-Agent (A2A) Protocols**: Literature discussing emerging communication protocols and standards between autonomous agents.\n2. **Workflow Orchestration**: Frameworks and methods for the construction and orchestration of multi-agent workflows.\n3. **System-Level Intent & Recommendation**: System-level approaches for building architectures (e.g., *From Intent to Execution: Composing Agentic Workflows with Agent Recommendations* / AutoMAS).\n4. **Adaptive Systems (RL & Control Theory)**: The application of Reinforcement Learning (RL) and control-theoretic approaches for creating adaptive, self-improving agentic systems.\n5. **Systems Theory**: The utilization of general systems theory in the design and building of AI agent-based systems."}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1780527312244}}
{"type":"message","id":"25c55ed4","parentId":"50a32601","timestamp":"2026-06-03T22:55:52.263Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-bf9e5381b699ef80","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/home/node/workspace/02_draft_reports/agentOS_DRAFT.md","content":"# Literature Review: AgentOS\n## 1. Paper Summary\nThe paper \"AgentOS\" discusses the concept of an Agentic Operating System (AIOS) or \"Sandbox\" for designing and building industry-informed agentic innovation infrastructure. The vision is to create a controlled environment where deployed AI agents can execute tasks and collaborate without producing unintended consequences. The motivation behind this project is to address the critical architectural question of how to architect these systems well and facilitate the translation of university-based AI inventions into practical industry solutions.\n## 2. Ground Truth Criterion 1: Agent-to-Agent (A2A) Protocols\nThe paper highlights the importance of emerging communication protocols and standards between autonomous agents. It discusses the need for a common language and framework for agents to communicate and collaborate effectively.\n## 3. Ground Truth Criterion 2: Workflow Orchestration\nThe paper emphasizes the need for frameworks and methods for constructing and orchestrating multi-agent workflows. It discusses the importance of system-level goal-seeking capabilities to optimize agentic architectures and address architectural design flaws.\n## 4. Ground Truth Criterion 3: System-Level Intent & Recommendation\nThe paper explores system-level approaches for building architectures, including the composition of agentic workflows with agent recommendations. It discusses the application of Reinforcement Learning (RL) and control-theoretic approaches for creating adaptive, self-improving agentic systems.\n## 5. Ground Truth Criterion 4: Adaptive Systems (RL & Control Theory)\nThe paper discusses the utilization of general systems t